# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aigosages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] The **Abrincatui** or **Abricantui** were a Gallic tribe dwelling in the south of the Cotentin Peninsula during the Roman period.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] They are mentioned as *Abrincatuos* by Pliny (1st c.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] AD), *’Abrinkátouoi* (’Aβρινκάτουοι) by Ptolemy (2nd c.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] AD), and as *Abrincatis* and *Abrincateni* in the *Notitia Dignitatum* (5th c.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] The city of Avranches, attested in the 6th c.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] AD as *civitas* *Abrincatum* ('civitas of the Abrincatui', *Abrincae* ca.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] 550, *de Avrenchis* in 1055–66), and the region of Avranchin, are named after the Gallic tribe.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] The territory of the Abrincatui mostly corresponded the later regions of Avranchin and Mortainais.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] It was inherited with only slight border changes by the *civitas* *Abrincatum* and, later, by the diocese of Avranches.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] However, the area of Mortainais was mostly uninhabited until the Roman period, and remained sparsely populated at the turn of the first millennium AD.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] Two pre-Roman oppida were located in Le Petit-Celland and Carolles, with other settlements in Montanel and near Mortain.
[src:aigosages/abrincatui] They were a client tribe of the Venelli until the Roman occupation in 49 BC, when they were separated.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] During a military engagement between Ptolemy III and Seleucus II, the precise circumstances of which are still unknown, his father Andromachus fell captive to Ptolemy III.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] Andromachus was eventually suggested to be a bargaining chip which would force Achaeus to join forces with Ptolemy against Seleucus, though at this stage Achaeus' loyalty was still unwavering.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] In 223 BC, Antiochus III, the successor of Seleucus III Ceraunus, appointed Achaeus to the command of all Asia Minor on the western side of Mount Taurus.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] Achaeus recovered all the districts which Attalus I had gained on the Seleucids once more, thereby destroying the aspirations of Attalus to become a major power, driving him back to the territory of Pergamum in 222 BC, and taking the whole of Asia on the western side of the Taurus.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] The fourth Syrian War and the preoccupation of Antiochus and his army with Ptolemy IV and Molon provided Achaeus the opportunity to declare himself king in Phrygia in the autumn of 220, thus finally severing the ties with Antiochus III.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] In 218 BC, Attalus regained control over the Greek cities of northern Ionia, Aeolis and Troas and the Mysian lands as far east as the Megistos river, which occupied Achaeus during the fourth Syrian war.
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] Upon the conclusion of a treaty with Ptolemy IV of Egypt, Antiochus crossed the Taurus in 216 BC, united his forces with Attalus, and in one campaign deprived Achaeus of his dominions and took Sardis (with the exception of the citadel).
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] After sustaining a siege of two years, the citadel at last fell into the hands of Antiochus in 214 BC, through the treachery of Bolis (who had been employed by Sosibius, minister to Ptolemy).
[src:aigosages/achaeus-general] Bolis pledged to deliver Achaeus to safety, but turned him over to Antiochus, who immediately put him to death.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] The **Acitavones** were a small Gallic tribe dwelling in the Alps during the Iron Age.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] They are mentioned as *Acitavones* (var.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] The etymology of the name *Acitauones* is unclear.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] The first element, *acito*-, could mean 'field' (cf.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] Old Irish *ached*, *achad*)*,* or else be a variant of *agido*- ('face, appearance').
[src:aigosages/acitavones] According to historian Guy Barruol, they may have dwelled in the Aosta Valley, near the Little St Bernard Pass.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] The *Barrington Atlas* locates their territory north of the Medulli and Segusini, south of the Veragri, west of the Salassi, and east of the Ceutrones.
[src:aigosages/acitavones] They are mentioned by Pliny the Elder as one of the Alpine tribes conquered by Rome in 16–15 BC, and whose name was engraved on the Tropaeum Alpium.
[src:aigosages/adanates] The **Adanates** or **Edenates** were a small Gallic tribe dwelling around present-day Seyne, in the Alpes Cottiae, during the Iron Age.
[src:aigosages/adanates] AD), and as *Adanatium* on the Arc of Susa.
[src:aigosages/adanates] The etymology of the name *Adanates* is unclear.
[src:aigosages/adanates] Guy Barruol has proposed to compare it with *Adenatius* (or *Adenatis*) and *Adana*, and postulated an original **Senedenates*, with loss of the initial *s-* retained in *Sedena*, the name of their chief town.
[src:aigosages/adanates] According to Alexander Falileyev, "if the original form was indeed **Sed-*, the name could be Celtic, from *sedo-* 'seat, location'; but in view of the form recorded in inscriptions, it is unlikely.
[src:aigosages/adanates] If *Eden-* is the original form, the name does not appear Celtic." Xavier Delamarre has proposed to interpret the name as *Ed-en-ati* ('those from the land/country'), from a Gaulish stem *edo-(n)-* ('space, land').
[src:aigosages/adanates] The Adanates dwelled around the settlement of Sedena (modern Seyne).
[src:aigosages/adanates] The *Barrington Atlas* locates their territory south of the Avantici, west of the Savincates, east of the Sebaginni, and north of the Gallitae and Eguiturii.
[src:aigosages/adanates] They also appear on the Arch of Susa, erected by Cottius in 9–8 BC.
[src:aigosages/adunicates] The **Adunicates** were a small Gallic tribe dwelling in the upper Durance valley during the Roman era.
[src:aigosages/adunicates] They are mentioned as *Adunicates* by Pliny (1st c.
[src:aigosages/adunicates] If Celtic, it may be interpreted as a haplology (loss of syllable) of Gaulish **Andedunicates*, based on the intensifying prefix *ande*-.
[src:aigosages/adunicates] In this view, it could be compared to the personal names *Andedunis* and *Atedunus* ('big fort').
[src:aigosages/adunicates] The Adunicates lived in the upper Durance valley.
[src:aigosages/adunicates] They are mentioned by Pliny as living near the Suetrii and the Quariates, north of the Oxybii and Ligauni.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The **Aedui** or **Haedui** (Gaulish: **Aiduoi*, 'the Ardent') were a Gallic people dwelling in central-eastern Gaul, in the country between the Loire and the Saône (modern Burgundy), during the Iron Age and the Roman period.
[src:aigosages/aedui] From the middle of the 2nd century BC they were allies of Rome, the first people of inner Gaul to conclude a formal treaty (*foedus*) with the Republic and, according to Tacitus, the only Gauls to bear the title *fratres populi Romani* ('brothers of the Roman people').
[src:aigosages/aedui] During the Gallic Wars (58–50 BC) they gave Caesar important if uneven support before briefly joining the revolt of Vercingetorix in 52 BC.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Their aristocracy was thereafter rapidly integrated into the Roman order, and under Claudius in 48 AD they were the first Gauls admitted to the Roman Senate.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Their principal *oppidum*, Bibracte on Mont Beuvray, was replaced under Augustus by a new capital, Augustodunum (Autun).
[src:aigosages/aedui] They are mentioned as *Haedui* by Cicero (mid-1st c.
[src:aigosages/aedui] AD), *Aidúōn* (Αἰδύων) by Ptolemy (2nd c.
[src:aigosages/aedui] AD), and as *Aídouoi* (Aἴδουοι) by Cassius Dio (3rd c.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The ethnonym *Aedui* is a Latinized form of Gaulish **Aiduoi* (sing.
[src:aigosages/aedui] It derives from the Celtic stem **aidu-* ('fire, ardour', cf.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Old Irish *áed* 'fire', Welsh *aidd* 'ardour'), itself from Proto-Indo-European: **h₂eydʰos* ('firewood', cf.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Sanskrit *édhas* 'bonfire', Latin *aedes* 'building, temple').
[src:aigosages/aedui] The Aedui held a central position in eastern Gaul, on the watershed dividing the Mediterranean, Atlantic and Channel drainage basins.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Their territory was bounded on the west by the Loire (*Liger*), which separated them from the Bituriges, and on the east by the Saône (*Arar*), which separated them from the Sequani.
[src:aigosages/aedui] To the south lay their clients the Segusiavi and the first foothills of the Massif Central, held by the Arverni, and to the north the edge of the Morvan and the country of their clients the Mandubii.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The river ports of *Cabillonum* (Chalon-sur-Saône) and *Matisco* (Mâcon) controlled the traffic of the Saône.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The Saône did not, however, form a stable linear frontier.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The river was easily forded and presented no real obstacle.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The boundary between Aedui and Sequani was sinuous rather than parallel to its course, with Aeduan enclaves on the eastern bank (notably around Chalon and Verdun) and Sequanian holdings to the west.
[src:aigosages/aedui] A weakly occupied zone south of Chalon, on the Bresse side, seems to have formed a kind of march separating the two peoples.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Three oppida are known from the end of the La Tène period: Vieux-Dun (Dun-les-Places), Le Fou de Verdun (Lavault-de-Frétoy), and Bibracte, which occupied a central position in the Aedian economic system.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Bibracte, the principal *oppidum* of the Aedui, occupied an isolated hill of the Morvan (Mont Beuvray, culminating at 820 m) at the meeting point of the basins of the Yonne, the Loire, the Seine and the Saône.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Occupied and probably fortified since the Neolithic, it reached its height in the 1st century BC before being progressively abandoned towards the end of that century in favour of Augustodunum.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The interior was hierarchically arranged, with sanctuaries on the highest points, aristocratic residences and the market on the plateau.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The craft quarters were located lower down, near the gates and in the outer suburb between the two lines of rampart.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Augustodunum's earliest urban occupation barely predates the turn of the era.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Only a small and unevenly distributed part of the urban area, of the order of one per cent, has been excavated down to the earliest levels as of 2015, so that the picture of the Julio-Claudian town remains very incomplete.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Before the Roman conquest the Aedui were one of the major political and military powers of central Gaul, contending for a preeminence with their powerful neighbours, the Sequani, Bituriges and Arverni.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Their *civitas* was an oligarchy in which the conduct of affairs lay with a senate, an assembly probably made up of the representatives of the great families, which had replaced the older assembly of the people in arms, convened only in exceptional cases such as a declaration of war.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Current business and the administration of justice lay with an annual magistrate, the *vergobret*, elected for one year, probably by the senate.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The names of several holders are known: Dumnorix (ca.
[src:aigosages/aedui] 60 BC), Liscos (58 BC), Valetiacos (53 BC), and Cotos, whose contested election in 52 BC was settled by Caesar in favour of his rival Convictolitavis.
[src:aigosages/aedui] A law forbade the supreme magistrate to leave the territory of the *civitas*.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The farming of taxes and tolls was let by auction.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The Aedui concluded an alliance with Rome at an undetermined moment around 150–140 BC.
[src:aigosages/aedui] With the Remi they were the traditional allies of Rome in Gaul, and according to Livy they were already allied with the Republic before 121 BC, when Domitius Ahenobarbus invoked the alliance in order to campaign against the Allobroges.
[src:aigosages/aedui] They were the first people of inner Gaul to contract such an alliance and, according to Tacitus, the only Gauls to bear the title *fratres populi Romani*.
[src:aigosages/aedui] This title was granted at the moment the *foedus* was concluded and reconfirmed by successive decrees of the Senate.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The treaty was a *foedus aequum*, an equal treaty resting on reciprocal *fides* between two peoples whose territories were not contiguous.
[src:aigosages/aedui] It entailed mutual military assistance together with the right of hospitality (*hospitalitas*).
[src:aigosages/aedui] Caesar called the Aedui consanguineous brothers (*fratres consanguinei*).
[src:aigosages/aedui] The alliance brought lasting Roman influence, as shown by a silver coinage aligned on the denarius and the early introduction of Roman-style architecture at Bibracte, a site that Olivier Buchsenschutz has described as a bridgehead of Roman influence towards the north of Gaul.
[src:aigosages/aedui] In 61 BC the Aeduan noble Diviciacus appealed to the Roman Senate for help against the Sequani, Arverni and Germani, but in vain.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Diviciacus, brother of Dumnorix and a partisan of Rome, had been received at Rome by Cicero, who records that he was a Druid.
[src:aigosages/aedui] He became Caesar's trusted intermediary.
[src:aigosages/aedui] When the Helvetii resolved to migrate to the country of the Santones across Aeduan territory, the *foedus* served Caesar as a pretext to intervene in the still unconquered part of Gauls (*Gallia comata*).
[src:aigosages/aedui] At the Aedui's request Caesar intervened in 58 BC against the Germani of Ariovistus, then allied with the Sequani within an Arvernian coalition.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Diviciacus guided the Roman legions into Alsace for the decisive battle.
[src:aigosages/aedui] His brother Dumnorix led the anti-Roman faction.
[src:aigosages/aedui] As son-in-law of the Helvetian Orgetorix, he had held the supreme magistracy shortly before 58 BC and had farmed the Aeduan tolls and taxes for several consecutive years.
[src:aigosages/aedui] His wealth allowed him to maintain a body of cavalry as a personal guard, and he commanded the Aeduan cavalry furnished to Caesar.
[src:aigosages/aedui] His collusion with the Helvetii was treated as treason, and he was spared only through his brother's influence.
[src:aigosages/aedui] In 54 BC, at *Portus Itius* (Boulogne), he refused to embark for Britain and was killed in flight, crying that he was a free man belonging to a free people.
[src:aigosages/aedui] During the war the Aedui were divided, supporting the Romans most of the time but also the insurgents during the brief revolt of 52 BC.
[src:aigosages/aedui] After Caesar's final victory they kept their laws and their title of *fratres populi Romani*.
[src:aigosages/aedui] As allies, the Aedui were not conquered but received Roman citizenship directly.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Their capital was transferred from Bibracte to a new town, Augustodunum (Autun), created *ex nihilo* on the order of Augustus at the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:aigosages/aedui] It lay about twenty kilometres west of Bibracte, on the road laid out under Agrippa.
[src:aigosages/aedui] From its creation the city was enclosed by a wall some 6 kilometres long delimiting nearly 200 hectares, a privilege normally reserved for Latin or Roman colonies.
[src:aigosages/aedui] It took the name of its founder: Augustodunum ('the town of Augustus'), from the Gaulish suffix *-dunum* ('town, fortress').
[src:aigosages/aedui] The legal status of the city is disputed.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Pliny lists it among the federated communities (*civitates foederatae*), but Antony Hostein, treating Pliny's testimony with caution, argues that the *civitas* held the status of a Latin-right colony from early on, perhaps from its foundation.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Excavation suggests that the move was a gradual shift rather than a sudden abandonment: the public buildings and craft quarters were transferred first in the last decade BC.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The aristocratic habitat moved later, only a sparse occupation remaining on the old *oppidum* after about 15 BC.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Under Claudius, a delegation of Gallic notables (the *primores Galliae*, designated by the council of the Ara Romae at Lyon) petitioned the emperor and the Senate in 48 AD for the right to pursue a senatorial career at Rome.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Claudius supported the request, but the Senate granted access not to the notables of all Three Gauls but to the Aedui alone as old allies The Aedui thus became the first Gauls to obtain the right to sit in the Roman Senate.
[src:aigosages/aedui] In 269–270 AD, Augustodunum was besieged for seven months and sacked.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The city had declared for the legitimate emperor Claudius II, the Aedui being the first to solicit his help to recover the Gauls against the Gallic emperor Victorinus.
[src:aigosages/aedui] Defended by its population, the city fell when the relief it awaited failed to arrive.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The repression that followed included the proscription of the city's notables and the confiscation of their property.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The city was restored under the Tetrarchy and Constantine, and in 312 it was renamed *Flavia Aeduorum* in honour of Constantine.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The only Druid named among the Aedui is Diviciacus, whom Cicero received at Rome and recorded as a member of the order.
[src:aigosages/aedui] At Augustodunum, inscriptions attest the cult of the goddess Bibracte, who bears the name of the former *oppidum*, of Anvallos, and the presence of a temple of Apollo.
[src:aigosages/aedui] The Temple of Janus, probably erected second half of the 1st century AD, was located just outside Augustodunum.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] Aeolis was an ancient district on the western coast of Asia Minor.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] It extended along the Aegean Sea from the entrance of the Hellespont (now the Dardanelles) south to the Hermus River (now the Gediz River).
[src:aigosages/aeolis] It was named for the Aeolians, some of whom migrated there from Greece before 1000 BC.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] Aeolis was, however, an ethnological and linguistic enclave rather than a geographical unit.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] The district often was considered part of the larger northwest region of Mysia.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] According to Homer's *Odyssey*, Odysseus, after his stay with the Cyclopes, reached the floating island of Aeolia, where Aeolus son of Hippotas provided him with the west wind Zephyrus.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] By the 8th century BC the Aeolians' twelve most important cities were independent.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] They formed a league of twelve cities (a Dodecapolis): Cyme (also called Phriconis), Larissa, Neonteichos, Temnos, Cilla, Notion, Aegiroessa, Pitane, Aegae, Myrina, Gryneion, and Smyrna.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] The most celebrated of the cities was Smyrna (modern İzmir, Turkey), but in 699 BC, Smyrna became part of an Ionian confederacy.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] This league or confederation, known as the *Ionian League*, also called the *Panionic League*, was formed at the end of the Meliac War in the mid-7th century BC.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] Croesus, king of Lydia (reigned 560–546 BC), conquered the remaining cities.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] Later they were held successively by the Persians, Macedonians, Seleucids, and Pergamenes.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] Attalus III, the last king of Pergamum, bequeathed Aeolis to the Roman Republic in 133 BC.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] Shortly afterwards it became part of the Roman province of Asia.
[src:aigosages/aeolis] At the partition of the Roman Empire (395 AD), Aeolis was assigned to the East Roman (Byzantine) empire and remained largely under Byzantine rule until the early 15th century, when the Ottoman Turks occupied the area.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The **Aigosages** (Ancient Greek: Αἰγοσάγες; also *Aegosages*) were a Gallic people of the early Hellenistic period, known almost solely from Polybius.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] A tribal group from Thrace, they were brought across the Hellespont in 218 BC by Attalus I of Pergamon to serve as mercenaries in his war against the Seleucid rebel Achaeus.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] After a mutiny they were settled on the Hellespont, where they raided the Troad and besieged Ilium, and they were destroyed by Prusias I of Bithynia about 216 BC.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] They are named as *Aigosages* (Αἰγοσάγες) by Polybius.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The name is formed with Gaulish the suffix *sagi*- ('seeking'), as in the Galatian tribes *Tectosages* and *Rigosages*.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The meaning of the first element is uncertain.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] Unlike the Tolistobogii, Tectosages and Trocmi who settled permanently in Galatia, the Aigosages formed a separate body recruited from south-eastern Europe.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The Aigosages were settled in Thrace, where they may have been among the Celts established since the great expedition into the Balkans, perhaps refugees from the kingdom of Tylis, which collapsed in 218 BC.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The aim was to win back the cities of Aeolis that had been intimidated into revolt by Achaeus.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The campaign was at first successful, most communities rejoining Attalus with little resistance.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] At the river Megistus, however, a lunar eclipse, datable to 1 September 218 BC, caused the mercenaries to mutiny.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] The tribe had crossed over in its entirety, accompanied by a slow-moving baggage train of wives, children and possessions, and was ill-suited to a rapid campaign.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] Despite the mutiny, Attalus settled the Aigosages on the Hellespont, in fulfilment of the obligations he had entered into.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] From there the Aigosages conducted raids of their own in the Troad and along the Hellespont, against which Attalus took no action.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] In 217 or 216 BC they besieged Ilium, but the siege failed, the walls built by Lysimachus holding, and the city was not sacked.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] Soon afterwards Prusias I of Bithynia annihilated the tribe, the force he sent against them numbering 4,000.
[src:aigosages/aigosages] Polybius synchronises the destruction with the consular elections of Varro and Paullus and the flight of Philip V from a Roman squadron near Apollonia, that is about 216 BC, though the precise date is disputed and proposals range from 217 to 212 BC.
